==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|condamner}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|condemnāre||to sentence, condemn, blame}}, from {{m|la|com-}} + {{m|la|damnāre||to harm, condemn, damn}}, from {{m|la|damnum||damage, injury, loss}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-condemn.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɛm|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{label|en|transitive}} To confer some sort of [[eternal]] divine punishment upon.
# {{label|en|transitive}} To adjudge (a building) as being unfit for habitation.
#: ''The house was '''condemned''' after it was badly damaged by fire.''
# {{label|en|transitive}} To scold sharply; to excoriate the perpetrators of.
#: ''The president '''condemns''' the terrorist.''
#: ''The president '''condemns''' the terrorist attacks.''
# {{label|en|transitive}} To judicially pronounce (someone) guilty.
# {{label|en|transitive}} To determine and declare (property) to be assigned to public use. See [[eminent domain]]
# {{label|en|transitive}} To adjudge (food or drink) as being unfit for human consumption.
# {{label|en|transitive|legal}} To declare (a vessel) to be forfeited to the government, to be a prize, or to be unfit for service.

